<div id="mast">
<div class="content">
<h2 class="article-title" id="d59611e2">The Allure of Gothic Markup</h2>
<h3 class="subtitle">
<i>Prioritizing Local Adaptation</i>
</h3>
<div class="author">
<h3 class="author">Simon St.Laurent</h3>
<div class="affiliation">
<p class="jobtitle">Senior Editor</p>
<p class="orgname">O'Reilly Media, Inc.</p>
</div>
<h5 class="author-email">
<code class="email">&lt;<a class="email" href="mailto:simonstl@simonstl.com">simonstl@simonstl.com</a>&gt;</code>
</h5>
</div>
<div class="legalnotice-block">
<p id="d59611e46">Copyright &copy; 2013 Simon St.Laurent. Permission for reuse readily granted.</p>
</div>
<div class="mast-box">
<p class="title">
<a href="javascript:toggle('d59611e12')" class="quiet"><img class="toc-icon" src="../../../icons/plus.png" alt="expand" id="icon-d59611e12"></a> <span onclick="javascript:toggle('d59611e12');return true">Abstract</span>
</p>
<div class="folder" id="folder-d59611e12" style="display:none">
<p id="d59611e13">XML inherited and worsened SGML's legalistic tendencies, promoting a world of markup built to industrial standards.  The sad reality of schemas is that they offer a defective transformation, one so crippled that it dehumanizes people working with them while giving us a broken impression of the world.  We can still escape, but need to openly shift from falsely static globals to a world of local adaptation and transformation.</p>
</div>
</div>
